10/21/2024,748.685(a)(4) - Individual Standards Evaluated,Individual Standards Evaluated,No,12/03/2024,12/03/2024,Individual Standards Evaluated,High,Yes,"Child in care was left unattended on a changing table, which resulted in the child falling of the changing table to the ground.","Email was sent to Inspector on 12/3/24 from Treatment Director Storm Rivas with the following information regarding deficiency and technical assistance given: To ensure compliance, as well as to provide the highest quality of care possible to the children within our facility, Respite Care of San Antonio has implemented several preventative measures to ensure adequate supervision is always maintained. All staff member(s) involved in this deficiency will also undergo mandatory retraining on RCSAs supervision policies. This is non-negotiable and must be completed within 14 days of assignment. Failure to do so may result in progressive discipline or removal from the schedule. 

To ensure compliance, as well as to provide the highest quality of care possible to the children within our facility, Respite Care of San Antonio has implemented several preventative measures to ensure adequate supervision is always maintained. All staff member(s) involved in this deficiency will also undergo mandatory retraining on RCSAs supervision policies. This is non-negotiable and must be completed within 14 days of assignment. Failure to do so may result in progressive discipline or removal from the schedule. As a reminder, all caregivers are required to maintain line of sight supervision during any instance that child is on an elevated surface. These surfaces include but are not limited to changing tables, playground equipment, or any other surface that a fall could reasonably cause injury from that height. All staff members are also reminded to utilize proper safety straps while using changing tables or playground equipment. Failure to do so may result in progressive disciplinary action. 

Remember, staff members are encouraged to communicate with one another to ensure children are adequately supervised at all times. There may be instances in which a staff member is requested by their supervisor or colleague to complete an assignment or task that could result in a lapse in supervision. Should this occur, that staff member is encouraged to maintain supervision regardless of the request. No assignment within the facility is more important than ensuring the safety of our children. No supervisor or colleague should also make a request that could hinder the supervision of children knowingly. These instances serve to further exhibit the importance of effective communication when caring for our children. For any questions, please contact the treatment director or quality improvement specialist directly. 
